<HEADLINE>
AMIS CULTURE EXHIBITION OPENS IN KAOHSIUNG
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kaohsiung,  May 27 (CNA) 05/27/07  16:54:44 (By Y.L. Kao)
</P>
<P>
An exhibition featuring plants used by the Amis, Taiwan's biggest
aboriginal tribe, to build houses and make clothes, is being held
at the National Science and Technology Museum in the southern
port city of Kaohsiung, organizers said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition,  titled "The Botanical  World of the Amis
Aborigines, " is being organized by National Taitung University
in the eastern county of Taitung and the Aboriginal Education
Research Center.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition opened Saturday, with Amis shaman Lo Fu-chin
performing  a blessing ceremony in which rice wine and other
sacrifices were offered to the gods. After that he presented
visitors with the sacred rice wine and wished everyone good luck.
</P>
<P>
Guo Chorng-Jee, president of National Taitung University, said
there is a growing trend among English-speaking  countries to
interpret aboriginal cultures through scientific views.
</P>
<P>
He added that the exhibition was organized to display wide
variety of cultural items made by Taitung's Amis people to show
how they use plants in their daily lives and to present the close
relationship between Amis culture and the plants they use.
</P>
<P>
A building constructed using plant materials and Amis skills is
also being showcased in the exhibition, as well as clothes made
with bark and fiber and a clothes-making workshop.
</P>
